english:
  title: 'Preface to the Jeonggugjeon: A Treatise on Governing Joseon'
  author: Jung Jong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Six Canons have existed since ancient times. Looking back to the Zhou Rites, we find: The first, the Canon of Administration, establishes order in the realm, governs the offices, and records all people. The second, the Canon of Education, stabilizes the realm, instructs the officials, and nurtures all people. The third, the Canon of Ritual, brings harmony to the realm, unifies the hundred offices, and harmonizes all people. The fourth, the Canon of Governance, pacifies the realm, rectifies the officials, and equalizes all people. The fifth, the Canon of Punishment, holds the realm accountable, serves as example for officials, and inspects all people. The sixth, the Canon of Works, enriches the realm, entrusts tasks to officials, and sustains all people. Administration governs through officers, Education through ritual, Governance through military affairs, and Works through craftsmanship. From antiquity to the present, the order and chaos, rise and fall of all lands and nations are clear for us to examine. Those that prospered and endured did so because they illuminated the Six Canons. Those that descended into chaos and perished did so because they were ignorant of the Six Canons.

    In the twilight of Goryeo, governance and transformation grew lax, the systems of order crumbled, and the Six Canons existed in name only, emptied of substance. For long, those of noble purpose wrung their hands and sighed in lament. Yet when disorder reaches its extreme, restoration becomes inevitable—such is the natural principle. Our sovereign, responding to Heaven's will and following the people's desires, has eliminated cruelty and abolished tyranny. He has reformed all corrupt practices and renewed our teachings. By regularly evaluating merit and removing the unworthy while advancing the worthy, the Canon of Administration shines clear. By reducing labor services and lessening taxes to nurture the people's livelihood, the Canon of Education shines clear. By establishing proper distinctions in carriages and robes, with clear ranks between high and low, we may say the Canon of Ritual shines clear. By skillfully managing the military and repelling invaders, we may say the Canon of Governance shines clear. When punishments align with the truth and the people suffer no injustice or oppression, the Canon of Punishment cannot be said to be dim. When all crafts and works are well managed and all endeavors flourish, the Canon of Works cannot be said to be dim.

    Thereupon, the Minister in charge of Three Departments, the Viscount of Bonghwa, our subject Jeong Do-jeon, compiled this work and named it the Jeonggugjeon. He presented it to our sovereign, whose gracious heart was pleased. He commanded that it be placed in a golden chest and entrusted to the proper authorities. He then commanded me, Jung Jong, to write this preface to its beginning.

    I humbly reflect that whenever an age rises, it must have the institutions and systems of that age. Unless a wise ruler and capable minister meet as naturally as fish takes to water, how could such achievement be possible? Now our sovereign opens his sincere heart and entrusts his ministers with authority. The Three Ministers, through their learning of Heaven and humanity and their talent for governance, have assisted in establishing the great foundation. With their refined and eloquent words, they have completed this great code. This work serves not only to aid our sovereign's evening contemplation, but will be a mirror and guide for all descendants through ten thousand generations. Ah, how excellent is this!

    Yet if one regards this merely as fine writing, then the book remains separate from the man, the man separate from the book—what then would it contribute to the way of governance? When Zisi composed the Doctrine of the Mean, he discussed the Nine Virtues, saying: "That by which these are practiced is one. What is this one?" He answered: "Sincerity." So too do I speak of this book with this same meaning in mind.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Six Canons (육전) refer to the six foundational systems of governance outlined in the Zhou Rites, representing the comprehensive administrative structure of ancient China that influenced Korean statecraft.
  - key: ''
    value: This preface was written by Jung Jong to accompany Jeong Do-jeon's Jeonggugjeon, a foundational administrative code of the early Joseon dynasty, presented to King Taejo.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to fish and water (魚水之歡) is a classical metaphor for the perfect harmony between a ruler and his ministers.
  - key: ''
    value: The final reference to Zisi (子思) and the Doctrine of the Mean emphasizes that sincerity (誠) is the ultimate principle underlying all proper governance and administration.
